   EVALUATION OF n + 204HG CROSS SECTIONS FOR THE ENERGY          8049 1451
                  RANGE 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV                        8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
       S. Chiba, M. B. Chadwick, and P. G. Young                  8049 1451
             JAERI and LANL laboratories                          8049 1451
                    1 June 1998                                   8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       8049 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               8049 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       8049 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     8049 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
            INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                    8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the          8049 1451
HG-204 evaluation for JENDL-3.3 by K. Shibata, T. Fukahori,       8049 1451
S. Chiba and N. Yamamuro, documented in (Sh97).                   8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
             INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                   8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        8049 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             8049 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    8049 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   8049 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  8049 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    8049 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    8049 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        8049 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      8049 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   8049 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     8049 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                8049 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   8049 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           8049 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         8049 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      8049 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         8049 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      8049 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n,p +  8049 1451
Hg  reactions. We use the GNASH code system                       8049 1451
(Yo92), which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical, preequilib-   8049 1451
rium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical model        8049 1451
calculations are used to obtain particle transmission             8049 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     8049 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    8049 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    8049 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  8049 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       8049 1451
(Ka88).                                                           8049 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  8049 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations (Ch96).  The recoil   8049 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  8049 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     8049 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   8049 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  8049 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             8049 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  8049 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach (Ka77,      8049 1451
Ka85), validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  8049 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     8049 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     8049 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk et al. (Ig75) and pairing and   8049 1451
shell parameters from the Cook (Co67) analysis. Neutron and       8049 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    8049 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            8049 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   8049 1451
model (Ko90).                                                     8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
     SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE HG-204 EVALUATION        8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  Because of the very limited amount of experimental data for     8049 1451
nucleon reactions on mercury, the evaluated data depended heavily 8049 1451
on nuclear model calculations with GNASH. An optical model        8049 1451
originally developed by S. Chiba for neutron scattering on lead   8049 1451
was adapted for use on mercury. This potential was used for the   8049 1451
total, nonelastic, and elastic scattering distributions. For      8049 1451
protons, the medium energy Madland potential (Ma88) was used      8049 1451
above 20 MeV, and the Becchetti-Greenlees potential (Be69) at     8049 1451
lower energies. Other potentials used were: Lohr (Lo74) for       8049 1451
deuterons, Becchetti (Be71) for tritons and helium3, and          8049 1451
McFadden-Satchler (Ma66) for alpha-particles.                     8049 1451
                                                                  8049 1451
  Deformation lengths for inelastic scattering were obtained from 8049 1451
the <20 MeV analyses performed for the  JENDL evaluation:         8049 1451
K. Shibata, T. Fukahori, S. Chiba and N. Yamamuro: "              8049 1451
Evaluation of Neutron Nuclear Data for Mercury",                  8049 1451
